title: Urge the Senate to pass HB 220/SB 1899: Strengthening Care for Sexual Assault Survivors
description:
HB 220/SB 1899 ensures that survivors of sexual assault receive the care they need and deserve when they seek medical attention. HB 220 has passed out of the House, but we need Chairmen Hughes to schedule it for a Senate State Affairs hearing ASAP! 

This bill would require Texas health care facilities to provide access to emergency contraception if clinically indicated and consent given, a private space when available, and the option to shower after a forensic exam. These are basic, trauma-informed protections that support survivors in their healing process.

College students and young people face a higher risk of sexual violence, yet many do not receive adequate care when they seek help. HB 220 takes a step toward ensuring all survivors in Texas are treated with the care and respect they deserve.

Chairmen Hughes needs to hear from you! Urge him to bring HB 220/SB 1899 for a hearing and demand better care for survivors.


Note: Once you hit "Send an Email" you should get an email pop-up allowing you to customize your message before sending it to the Chairmen Hughes. title: Protect NY's Climate Law - Syracuse
description:
Join Citizen Action of NY, PUSH Buffalo, NY Renews, Third Act Upstate New York, and local CNY groups to rally and testify at a DEC public hearing in Syracuse on June 3 at noon to defend NY‚Äôs Climate Law.

New Yorkers will join to voice their support for climate leadership and to urge Governor Hochul to stand up to Trump by funding climate legislation. Join us and help make this impactful by emailing egormley@citizenactionny.org.

The climate change-denier in the White House is doing everything he can to eliminate climate progress in this country. We need climate leadership in NY, and we need it now. Unfortunately, in January, Governor Hochul revealed that she‚Äôs delaying a crucial component of the state‚Äôs Climate Law called Cap and Invest. 


Cap and Invest is an emissions-reduction program that would limit, or cap, emissions from major polluters in the state. That cap would tighten over time, gradually reducing the amount of emissions allowed for release. Meanwhile, major polluters will have to pay to release polluting emissions up to the level of the cap. Those funds from polluters will then be used to invest in green energy, jobs, home decarbonization programs, and similar efforts to support NY communities.

To move Cap and Invest forward, we need the Department of Environmental Conservation (DEC) to release three sets of regulations that hold polluters accountable to Cap and Invest. Unfortunately, Governor Hochul has  released only one.
